### Step 1: Starting your Containerlab

You'll first need to log in to the shared server running at IPng Networks in Switzerland. Your
details (hostname, username, and password) are at the top of this manual.

Once logged in,  you can change to your Containerlab working directory which we've prepared for you.

```
$ cd ~/containerlab-p{{id}}/
$ clab deploy
```

After just a few moments, the LAB will be started for you. You can see which nodes are available to
you, there will be three: `vpp1`, `vpp2` and `client`. Your lab has a unique prefix, which allows
multiple participants to work on the same server as you:

*   Your `vpp1` node is called `zanog-p{{id}}-vpp1`
*   Your `vpp2` node is called `zanog-p{{id}}-vpp2`
*   Your `client` linux host is called `zanog-p{{id}}-client`

You can connect to them using `clabc` (which stands for _containerlab client_). For example, to
connect to the `vpp2` node, use:

```
$ clabc vpp2
root@vpp2:/# vppctl show version
vpp v26.06-rc0~384-g0d14316cb built by pim on summer at 2026-03-29T18:37:04
root@vpp2:/# exit
$
```

You can take a look around on your `vpp2` node. You'll find that VPP keeps it configuration files in
a directory called `/config/vpp/` and Bird2, a routing daemon that is used for OSPF and BGP, keeps
its configuration files in a directory called `/config/bird/`. In the next steps, we will complete
the configuration files in these directories.

