### Step 2: Connecting client to VPP2

![step2](Containerlab Step 2.svg)

In this step you will configure `vpp2` to complete the connection to the `client` node. VPP is
configured using the file `/config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml`. Open this file with an editor of your choice,
like `nano` or `vim`. We're going to assign an IPv4 and IPv6 address to the `eth2` interface, see
the red circle in the diagram above.

For this subnet between `client` and `vpp2`, we will be using:

*    IPv4: `10.0.{{id}}.64/28` where `vpp2` is `.65` and `client` is already `.66`
*    IPv6: `2001:db8:{{ '%x' % id }}:100::/64` where `vpp2` is `::1` and `client` is already `::2`

If you've edited the file correctly, it should look like this:

```
root@vpp2:/# nano /config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml
interfaces:
  eth1:
    description: 'To vpp1'
    mtu: 1500
    lcp: eth1
  eth2:
    description: 'To client'
    mtu: 1500
    lcp: eth2
>>    addresses: [ 10.0.{{id}}.65/28, 2001:db8:{{ '%x' % id }}:100::1/64 ]
loopbacks:
  loop0:
    description: 'vpp2'
    lcp: loop0
```

The line to add is marked in bright green. There's a utility called `vppcfg` which can apply this
configuration to VPP. You can see what it would change by running the `vppcfg plan` command:

```
root@vpp2:/# vppcfg plan
```

And you can commit the configuration to the router with the `vppcfg apply` command:

```
root@vpp2:/# vppcfg apply
```

If you successfully committed the configuration, you should be able to ping the `client` node:

```
root@vpp2:/# ip -br a
lo               UNKNOWN        127.0.0.1/8 ::1/128 
loop0            UP             fe80::dcad:ff:fe00:0/64 
eth1             UNKNOWN        fe80::a8c1:abff:fe69:750d/64 
>>eth2             UNKNOWN        10.0.{{id}}.65/28 2001:db8:{{'%x' % id}}:100::1/64 fe80::a8c1:abff:fe11:748f/64

root@vpp2:/# ping 10.0.{{id}}.66
root@vpp2:/# ping 2001:db8:{{'%x' % id}}:100::2
```

The addresses you just applied are shown in green above. When issuing the `ping` commands,
you should see responses from both the IPv4 and IPv6 addresses. That's the `client` node responding.

