### Step 3: Connecting VPP2 to VPP1

![Step 3](Containerlab Step 3.svg)

In this step you will connect `vpp2:eth1` to `vpp1:eth2`, by configuring an IPv4 and IPv6 address on
each interface in file `/config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml`. See the red circle in the diagram above. For this
subnet between `vpp1` and `vpp2`, you will be using:

*    IPv4: `10.0.{{id}}.16/31` where `vpp1:eth2` is `.16` and `vpp2:eth1` is `.17`
*    IPv6: `2001:db8:{{ '%x' % id }}:1::/64` where `vpp1:eth2` is `::1` and `vpp2:eth1` is `::2`

Using the same approach as the previous step, edit the file, run `vppcfg plan` and then `vppcfg
apply`. Start with `vpp2`, the same router you edited in the previous step.

```
root@vpp2:/# nano /config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml
interfaces:
  eth1:
    description: 'To vpp1'
    mtu: 1500         
    lcp: eth1
>>    addresses: [ 10.0.{{id}}.17/31, 2001:db8:{{'%x' % id}}:1::2/64 ]
  eth2:
    description: 'To client'
    mtu: 1500
    lcp: eth2
    addresses: [ 10.0.{{id}}.65/28, 2001:db8:{{'%x' % id}}:100::1/64 ]
loopbacks:
  loop0:
    description: 'vpp2'
    lcp: loop0
```

Check the config with `vppcfg plan`, then commit it with `vppcfg apply`. This should complete the
configuration of `vpp2`.  Log out from it with `exit`, and then connect to `vpp1` and edit its `eth2` address:
```
root@vpp1:/# nano /config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml
interfaces:
  eth1:
    description: 'To vpplab shared LAN'
    mtu: 1500         
    lcp: eth1
  eth2:
    description: 'To vpp2'
    mtu: 1500
    lcp: eth2
>>    addresses: [ 10.0.{{id}}.16/31, 2001:db8:{{'%x' % id}}:1::1/64 ]
loopbacks:
  loop0:
    description: 'vpp1'
    lcp: loop0
root@vpp1:/# vppcfg plan
root@vpp1:/# vppcfg apply
```

Now that you've configured both sides of this link between `vpp2` and `vpp1`, you should be able to
ping `vpp2` from `vpp1` with both IPv4 and IPv6:

```
root@vpp1:/# ping 10.0.{{id}}.17
root@vpp1:/# ping 2001:db8:{{'%x' % id}}:1::2
```

