### Step 4: Enabling OSPF on VPP2

![Step 4](Containerlab Step 4.svg)

In this step you'll enable OSPF on `vpp2` for IPv4 and IPv6 by placing interface `loop0` and `eth1`
into the OSPF backbone area. First, you give the `loop0` interface an IPv4 and IPv6 address, by
editing `/config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml`:

```
root@vpp2:/# nano /config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml
...
loopbacks:
  loop0:
    description: 'vpp2'
    lcp: loop0
>>    addresses: [ 10.0.{{ id }}.2/32, 2001:db8:{{ '%x' % id }}::2/128 ]
```
After you've added the addresses marked in green above to the `loop0` interface, you can check the
configuration with `vppcfg plan` and then commit it with `vppcfg apply`.

Next, you will edit the Bird2 configuration file as follows:

```
root@vpp2:/# nano /config/bird/bird-local.conf
router id 10.0.{{ id }}.2;
protocol ospf v2 ospf4 {
  ipv4 { import all; export all; };
  area 0 {
    interface "loop0" { stub yes; };
    interface "eth1" { type pointopoint; cost 10; };
  };
}
protocol ospf v3 ospf6 {
  ipv6 { import all; export all; };
  area 0 {
    interface "loop0" { stub yes; };
    interface "eth1" { type pointopoint; cost 10; };
  };
}
```

You can check the configuration with `bird -p` and if there are no errors, you can commit it with
`birdc configure`. You should now see the new `ospf4` and `ospf6` protocols:

```
root@vpp2:/# birdc show proto
BIRD 2.18 ready.
Name       Proto      Table      State  Since         Info
device1    Device     ---        up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
direct1    Direct     ---        up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
kernel4    Kernel     master4    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
kernel6    Kernel     master6    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
>>ospf4      OSPF       master4    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  Alone
>>ospf6      OSPF       master6    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  Alone
```

It's OK that the router is **Alone**, this is because the other router `vpp1` hasn't been configured
yet. We'll do that next!

### Step 5: Enabling OSPF on VPP1

![Step 5](Containerlab Step 5.svg)

In this step you'll enable OSPF on `vpp1` for IPv4 and IPv6 by placing interface `loop0` and `eth2`
into the OSPF backbone area. First, you give the `loop0` interface an IPv4 and IPv6 address, by
editing `/config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml`:

```
root@vpp1:/# nano /config/vpp/vppcfg.yaml
...
loopbacks:
  loop0:
    description: 'vpp1'
    lcp: loop0
>>    addresses: [ 10.0.{{ id }}.1/32, 2001:db8:{{ '%x' % id }}::1/128 ]
```
After you've added the addresses marked in green above to the `loop0` interface, you can check the
configuration with `vppcfg plan` and then commit it with `vppcfg apply`. Next, you will edit the
Bird2 configuration file, in exactly the same way as the other router in the previous step, except
on `vpp1` you'll be adding `eth2`:

```
root@vpp1:/# nano /config/bird/bird-local.conf
router id 10.0.{{ id }}.1;
protocol ospf v2 ospf4 {
  ipv4 { import all; export all; };
  area 0 {
    interface "loop0" { stub yes; };
    interface "eth2" { type pointopoint; cost 10; };
  };
}
protocol ospf v3 ospf6 {
  ipv6 { import all; export all; };
  area 0 {
    interface "loop0" { stub yes; };
    interface "eth2" { type pointopoint; cost 10; };
  };
}
```

You can check the configuration with `bird -p` and if there are no errors, you can commit it with
`birdc configure`. You should now see the new `ospf4` and `ospf6` protocols:

```
root@vpp1:/# birdc show proto
BIRD 2.18 ready.
Name       Proto      Table      State  Since         Info
device1    Device     ---        up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
direct1    Direct     ---        up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
kernel4    Kernel     master4    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
kernel6    Kernel     master6    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
>>ospf4      OSPF       master4    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  Running
>>ospf6      OSPF       master6    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  Running
```

If you've done Step4+Step5 correctly, the routers will have found each other and formed an OSPF
adjacency. They will be exchanging routing information from now on. You can check this with:

```
root@vpp1:/# birdc show ospf neighbors
root@vpp1:/# birdc show route all
```

Once the routers have an OSPF adjacency, `vpp1` will be able to reach the `client` node via `vpp2`,
which you can validate with:

```
root@vpp1:/# ping 10.0.{{id}}.66
root@vpp1:/# ping 2001:db8:{{'%x' % id}}:100::2
```

