### Step 7: Enabling eBGP on VPP1

On the internet, BGP peers will accept typically only /24 or larger IPv4 prefixes, and /48 or larger
IPv6 prefixes. You have been assigned the following prefixes for your lab:

*    IPv4: `10.0.{{id}}.0/24`
*    IPv6: `2001:db8:{{'%x' % id }}::/48`
*    AS Number: `{{ 65000 + id }}`

BGP announcements can only occur if the router has a route for these prefixes. However, until now
you've configured only more-specifics (like the /32 or /128 on `loop0`). To address this and make
sure the aggregate prefixes are present in your routing table, you'll now configure them by adding
the following to your Bird config:

```
root@vpp1:/# nano /config/bird/bird-local.conf
protocol static static4 {
  ipv4 { export all; };
  route 10.0.{{ id }}.0/24 unreachable;
}

protocol static static6 {
  ipv6 { export all; };
  route 2001:db8:{{ '%x' % id }}::/48 unreachable;
}
```

You can check your work with `bird -p` and commit it with `birdc configure`. There is one last step,
and that's to configure the BGP sessions to the Teacher's lab, by adding them to the end of
`bird-local.conf`:

```
root@vpp1:/# nano /config/bird/bird-local.conf
protocol bgp ebgp_ipv4 {
    local 192.0.2.{{ id }} as {{ 65000 + id }};
    neighbor 192.0.2.254 as 65000;
    ipv4 { import all; export all; };
}

protocol bgp ebgp_ipv6 {
    local 2001:db8:8298::{{ '%x' % id }} as {{ 65000 + id }};
    neighbor 2001:db8:8298::fe as 65000;
    ipv6 { import all; export all; };
}
```

You can check your work with `bird -p` and commit it with `birdc configure`. After a few moments,
you will see the BGP sessions come up:

```
root@vpp1:/# birdc show proto
BIRD 2.18 ready.
Name       Proto      Table      State  Since         Info
device1    Device     ---        up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
direct1    Direct     ---        up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
kernel4    Kernel     master4    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
kernel6    Kernel     master6    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
static4    Static     master4    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
static6    Static     master6    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  
ospf4      OSPF       master4    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  Running
ospf6      OSPF       master6    up     2026-04-03 19:17:31  Running
>>ebgp_ipv4  BGP        ---        up     2026-04-03 19:17:39  Established   
>>ebgp_ipv6  BGP        ---        up     2026-04-03 19:17:39  Established   
```

You can check to see the new routes your VPP router is learning via BGP, like so:
```
root@vpp1:/# birdc show route all
```

If the sessions do not come up to **Established** state, don't worry. Ask a Teacher or assistant for
help. Getting BGP sessions can be tricky, but if you've followed these steps, you should see both
sessions up and running.

